Time series are everywhere! In user behavior on a website, or stock prices of a Fortune 500 company, or any other time-related example. Time series data is evident in every industry in some shape or form. \par
\par
Naturally, it\rquote s also one of the most researched types of data. As a rule of thumb, you could say time series is a type of data that\rquote s sampled based on some kind of time-related dimension like years, months, or seconds.\par
\par
Time series are observations that have been recorded in an orderly fashion and which are correlated in time.\par
\par
While analyzing time series data, we have to make sure of the outliers, much as we do in static data. If you\rquote ve worked with data in any capacity, you know how much pain outliers cause for an analyst. These outliers are called \ldblquote anomalies\rdblquote  in time series jargon.\par
\par
READ ALSO\par
Time Series Prediction: How Is It Different From Other Machine Learning?\par
\par
What are anomalies/outliers and types of anomalies in time-series data?\par
From a traditional point of view, an outlier/anomaly is:\par
\par
\ldblquote An observation which deviates so much from other observations as to arouse suspicions that it was generated by a different mechanism.\rdblquote\par
\par
Therefore, you can think of outliers as observations that don\rquote t follow the expected behavior.\par
\par
Time series outliers\par
As the figure above shows, outliers in time series can have two different meanings.  The semantic distinction between them is mainly based on your interest as the analyst, or the particular scenario. \par
\par
These observations have been related to noise, erroneous or unwanted data, which by itself isn\rquote t interesting to the analyst. In these cases, outliers should be deleted or corrected to improve data quality, and generate a cleaner dataset that can be used by other data mining algorithms. For example, sensor transmission errors are eliminated to obtain more accurate predictions, because the main goal is to make predictions. \par
\par
Nevertheless, in recent years \f1\endash  especially in the area of time series data \endash  many researchers have aimed to detect and analyze unusual, but interesting phenomena. Fraud detection is a good example \endash  the main objective is to detect and analyze the outlier itself. These observations are often referred to as anomalies.\par
\par
The anomaly detection problem for time series is usually formulated as identifying outlier data points relative to some norm or usual signal. Take a look at some outlier types:\par
\par
Time series outliers types\par
Let\rquote s break this down one by one:\par
\par
Point outlier\par
A point outlier is a datum that behaves unusually in a specific time instance when compared either to the other values in the time series (global outlier), or to its neighboring points (local outlier). \par
\par
Example: are you aware of the Gamestop frenzy? A slew of young retail investors bought GME stock to get back at big hedge funds, driving the stock price way up. That sudden, short-lived spike that occurred due to an unlikely event is an additive (point) outlier. The unexpected growth of a time-based value in a short period (looks like a sudden spike) comes under additive outliers.\par
\par
Time series point outlier\par
Source: Google\par
Point outliers can be univariate or multivariate, depending on whether they affect one or more time-dependent variables, respectively. \par
\par
Fig. 1a contains two univariate point outliers, O1 and O2, whereas the multivariate time series is composed of three variables in Fig. 3b, and has both univariate (O3) and multivariate (O1 and O2) point outliers.\par
\par
Point outliers in time series\par
\par
Fig: 1\u8202?\emdash\u8202?Point outliers in time series data. | Source\par
We will take a deeper look at Univariate Point Outliers in the Anomaly Detection section.\par
\par
Subsequence outlier\par
This means consecutive points in time whose joint behavior is unusual, although each observation individually is not necessarily a point outlier. Subsequence outliers can also be global or local, and can affect one (univariate subsequence outlier) or more (multivariate subsequence outlier) time-dependent variables. \par
\par
Fig. 2 provides an example of univariate (O1 and O2 in Fig. 2a, and O3 in Fig. 2b) and multivariate (O1 and O2 in Fig. 2b) subsequence outliers. Note that the latter does not necessarily affect all the variables (e.g., O2 in Fig. 2b).\par
\par
\u8202?Subsequence outliers in time series \par
Fig: 2\u8202?\emdash\u8202?Subsequence outliers in time series data. | Source\par
Anomaly detection techniques in time series data\par
There are few techniques that analysts can employ to identify different anomalies in data. It starts with a basic statistical decomposition and can work up to autoencoders. Let\rquote s start with the basic one, and understand how and why it\rquote s useful.\par
\par
NOTE\par
