\par
STL decomposition\par
STL stands for seasonal-trend decomposition procedure based on LOESS. This technique gives you the ability to split your time series signal into three parts: seasonal, trend, and residue.\par
\par
It works for seasonal time-series, which is also the most popular type of time series data. To generate an STL-decomposition plot, we just use the ever-amazing statsmodels to do the heavy lifting for us.\par
\par
plt.rc('figure',figsize=(12,8))\par
plt.rc('font',size=15)\par
result = seasonal_decompose(lim_catfish_sales,model='additive')\par
fig = result.plot()\par
STL decomposition\par
This is Catfish sales data from 1996\f1\endash 2000 with an anomaly introduced in Dec-1998\par
If we analyze the deviation of residue and introduce some threshold for it, we\rquote ll get an anomaly detection algorithm. To implement this, we only need the residue data from the decomposition.\par
\par
plt.rc('figure',figsize=(12,6))\par
plt.rc('font',size=15)\par
fig, ax = plt.subplots()\par
x = result.resid.index\par
y = result.resid.values\par
ax.plot_date(x, y, color='black',linestyle='--')\par
ax.annotate('Anomaly', (mdates.date2num(x[35]), y[35]), xytext=(30, 20),\par
