\par
Detection using Forecasting\par
Anomaly detection using Forecasting is based on an approach that several points from the past generate a forecast of the next point with the addition of some random variable, which is usually white noise. \par
\par
As you can imagine, forecasted points in the future will generate new points and so on. Its obvious effect on the forecast horizon \endash  the signal gets smoother.\par
\par
The difficult part of using this method is that you should select the number of differences, number of autoregressions, and forecast error coefficients.\par
\par
Each time you work with a new signal, you should build a new forecasting model.\par
\par
Another obstacle is that your signal should be stationary after differencing. In simple words, it means your signal shouldn\rquote t be dependent on time, which is a significant constraint.\par
\par
We can utilize different forecasting methods such as Moving Averages, Autoregressive approach, and ARIMA with its different variants. The procedure for detecting anomalies with ARIMA is:\par
\par
Predict the new point from past datums and find the difference in magnitude with those in the training data.\par
Choose a threshold and identify anomalies based on that difference threshold. That\rquote s it!\par
To test this technique, we\rquote re gonna use a popular module in time series called fbprophet. This module specifically caters to stationarity and seasonality, and can be tuned with some hyper-parameters.\par
\par
