The same Catfish Sales data but with different (multiple) anomalies introduced\par
We\rquote ll utilize the same data as we did above with the same anomalies. First, let\rquote s import it and make it ready for the environment:\par
\par
from fbprophet import Prophet\par
Now let\rquote s define the forecasting function. An important thing to note here is that fbprophet will add some additional metrics as features, in order to help identify anomalies better. For example, the predicted time series variable (by the model), the upper and lower limit of the target time series variable, and the trend metric.\par
\par
def fit_predict_model(dataframe, interval_width = 0.99, changepoint_range = 0.8):\par
   m = Prophet(daily_seasonality = False, yearly_seasonality = False, weekly_seasonality = False,\par
               seasonality_mode = 'additive',\par
               interval_width = interval_width,\par
               changepoint_range = changepoint_range)\par
   m = m.fit(dataframe)\par
   forecast = m.predict(dataframe)\par
   forecast['fact'] = dataframe['y'].reset_index(drop = True)\par
   return forecast\par
  \par
pred = fit_predict_model(t)\par
We now have to push the pred variable to another function, which will detect anomalies based on a threshold of lower and upper limit in the time series variable.\par
\par
def detect_anomalies(forecast):\par
   forecasted = forecast[['ds','trend', 'yhat', 'yhat_lower', 'yhat_upper', 'fact']].copy()\par
forecasted['anomaly'] = 0\par
   forecasted.loc[forecasted['fact'] > forecasted['yhat_upper'], 'anomaly'] = 1\par
   forecasted.loc[forecasted['fact'] < forecasted['yhat_lower'], 'anomaly'] = -1\par
#anomaly importances\par
   forecasted['importance'] = 0\par
   forecasted.loc[forecasted['anomaly'] ==1, 'importance'] = \\\par
       (forecasted['fact'] - forecasted['yhat_upper'])/forecast['fact']\par
   forecasted.loc[forecasted['anomaly'] ==-1, 'importance'] = \\\par
       (forecasted['yhat_lower'] - forecasted['fact'])/forecast['fact']\par
  \par
   return forecasted\par
pred = detect_anomalies(pred)\par
At last, we just need to plot the above predictions and visualize the anomalies.\par
