Anomaly detection\par
Pros\par
\par
This algorithm nicely handles different seasonality parameters like monthly or yearly, and it has native support for all time series metrics. \par
\par
If you look closely, this algorithm can handle edge cases well as compared to the Isolation Forest algorithm.\par
\par
Cons\par
\par
Since this technique is based on forecasting, it will struggle in limited data scenarios. The quality of prediction in limited data will be lower, and so will the accuracy of anomaly detection.\par
\par
Clustering-based anomaly detection\par
So far, we\rquote ve looked at the IsolationForest algorithm as our unsupervised way of anomaly detection. Now, we\rquote ll look into another unsupervised technique: Clustering! \par
\par
The approach is pretty straightforward. Data instances that fall outside of defined clusters could potentially be marked as anomalies. We\rquote re gonna use k-means clustering, because why not!\par
\par
For the sake of visualizations, we\rquote ll use a different dataset that corresponds to a multivariable time series with one or more time-based variables. The dataset will be a subset of the one found here (columns/features are the same).\par
\par
Dataset Description: Data contains information on shopping and purchase as well as information on price competitiveness.\par
\par
Now in order to process k-means, first we need to know the number of clusters we\rquote re gonna be dealing with. The Elbow Method works pretty efficiently for this.\par
\par
The Elbow method is a graph of the number of clusters vs the variance explained/objective/score\par
\par
To implement this, we\rquote ll use scikit-learn\rquote s implementation of K-means.\par
\par
data = df[['price_usd', 'srch_booking_window', 'srch_saturday_night_bool']]\par
n_cluster = range(1, 20)\par
kmeans = [KMeans(n_clusters=i).fit(data) for i in n_cluster]\par
scores = [kmeans[i].score(data) for i in range(len(kmeans))]\par
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))\par
ax.plot(n_cluster, scores)\par
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')\par
plt.ylabel('Score')\par
plt.title('Elbow Curve')\par
plt.show();\par
Elbow method\par
From the above elbow curve, we see that the graph levels off after 10 clusters, implying that the addition of more clusters do not explain much more of the variance in our relevant variable; in this case price_usd.\par
\par
We set n_clusters=10, and upon generating the k-means output, use the data to plot the 3D clusters.\par
\par
Anomaly detection k means\par
Now we need to find out the number of components (features) to keep.\par
\par
data = df[['price_usd', 'srch_booking_window', 'srch_saturday_night_bool']]\par
X = data.values\par
X_std = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)\par
#Calculating Eigenvecors and eigenvalues of Covariance matrix\par
mean_vec = np.mean(X_std, axis=0)\par
cov_mat = np.cov(X_std.T)\par
eig_vals, eig_vecs = np.linalg.eig(cov_mat)\par
# Create a list of (eigenvalue, eigenvector) tuples\par
eig_pairs = [ (np.abs(eig_vals[i]),eig_vecs[:,i]) for i in range(len(eig_vals))]\par
eig_pairs.sort(key = lambda x: x[0], reverse= True)\par
# Calculation of Explained Variance from the eigenvalues\par
tot = sum(eig_vals)\par
var_exp = [(i/tot)*100 for i in sorted(eig_vals, reverse=True)] # Individual explained variance\par
cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(var_exp) # Cumulative explained variance\par
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))\par
plt.bar(range(len(var_exp)), var_exp, alpha=0.3, align='center', label='individual explained variance', color = 'y')\par
plt.step(range(len(cum_var_exp)), cum_var_exp, where='mid',label='cumulative explained variance')\par
plt.ylabel('Explained variance ratio')\par
plt.xlabel('Principal components')\par
plt.legend(loc='best')\par
plt.show();\par
Anomaly detection components\par
We see that the first component explains almost 50% of the variance. The second component explains over 30%. However, notice that almost none of the components are really negligible. The first 2 components contain over 80% of the information. So, we will set n_components=2.\par
\par
The underlying assumption in the clustering-based anomaly detection is that if we cluster the data, normal data will belong to clusters while anomalies will not belong to any clusters, or belong to small clusters. \par
\par
We use the following steps to find and visualize anomalies:\par
\par
Calculate the distance between each point and its nearest centroid. The biggest distances are considered anomalies.\par
We use outliers_fraction to provide information to the algorithm about the proportion of the outliers present in our data set, similarly to the IsolationForest algorithm. This is largely a hyperparameter that needs hit/trial or grid-search to be set right \endash  as a starting figure, let\rquote s estimate, outliers_fraction=0.1\par
Calculate number_of_outliers using outliers_fraction.\par
Set the threshold as the minimum distance of these outliers.\par
The anomaly result of anomaly1 contains the above method Cluster (0:normal, 1:anomaly).\par
Visualize anomalies with cluster view.\par
Visualize anomalies with Time Series view.\par
# return Series of distance between each point and its distance with the closest centroid\par
def getDistanceByPoint(data, model):\par
   distance = pd.Series()\par
   for i in range(0,len(data)):\par
       Xa = np.array(data.loc[i])\par
       Xb = model.cluster_centers_[model.labels_[i]-1]\par
       distance.at[i]=np.linalg.norm(Xa-Xb)\par
   return distance\par
outliers_fraction = 0.1\par
# get the distance between each point and its nearest centroid. The biggest distances are considered as anomaly\par
distance = getDistanceByPoint(data, kmeans[9])\par
number_of_outliers = int(outliers_fraction*len(distance))\par
threshold = distance.nlargest(number_of_outliers).min()\par
# anomaly1 contain the anomaly result of the above method Cluster (0:normal, 1:anomaly)\par
df['anomaly1'] = (distance >= threshold).astype(int)\par
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))\par
colors = \{0:'blue', 1:'red'\}\par
ax.scatter(df['principal_feature1'], df['principal_feature2'], c=df["anomaly1"].apply(lambda x: colors[x]))\par
plt.xlabel('principal feature1')\par
plt.ylabel('principal feature2')\par
plt.show();\par
