Model specification\par
[25, 2, 2, 25]. The input layer and the output layer have 25 neurons each. There are two hidden layers, each has two neurons.\par
Step 1\u8202?\emdash\u8202?Build your model\par
\par
clf = AutoEncoder(hidden_neurons =[25, 2, 2, 25])\par
clf.fit(X_train)\par
Step 2\u8202?\emdash\u8202?Determine the cut point\par
\par
Let\rquote s apply the trained model Clf to predict the anomaly score for each observation in the test data. How do we define an outlier? An outlier is a point that\rquote s distant from other points, so the outlier score is defined by distance. The PyOD function .decision_function() calculates the distance, or the anomaly score, for each data point.\par
\par
# Get the outlier scores for the train data\par
y_train_scores = clf.decision_scores_\par
# Predict the anomaly scores\par
y_test_scores = clf.decision_function(X_test)  # outlier scores\par
y_test_scores = pd.Series(y_test_scores)\par
# Plot it!\par
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\par
plt.hist(y_test_scores, bins='auto') \par
plt.title("Histogram for Model Clf1 Anomaly Scores")\par
plt.show()\par
If we use a histogram to count the frequency by the anomaly score, we will see the high scores corresponds to a low frequency\u8202?\emdash\u8202?evidence of outliers. We choose 4.0 to be the cut point and those >=4.0 to be outliers.\par
\par
Anomaly detection histogram\par
Step 3\u8202?\emdash\u8202?Get the summary statistics by cluster\par
\par
Let\rquote s assign those observations with less than 4.0 anomaly scores to Cluster 0, and to Cluster 1 for those above 4.0. Also, let\rquote s calculate the summary statistics by cluster using .groupby() . This model has identified 50 outliers (not shown).\par
\par
df_test = X_test.copy()\par
df_test['score'] = y_test_scores\par
df_test['cluster'] = np.where(df_test['score']<4, 0, 1)\par
df_test['cluster'].value_counts()\par
df_test.groupby('cluster').mean()\par
The following output shows the mean variable values in each cluster. The values of Cluster \lquote 1\rquote  (the abnormal cluster) are quite different from those of Cluster \lquote 0\rquote  (the normal cluster). The \ldblquote score\rdblquote  values show the average distance of those observations to others. A high \ldblquote score\rdblquote  means that observation is far away from the norm.\par
\par
Anomaly detection cluster\par
This way, we can distinguish and label pretty perfectly between typical datums and anomalies.\par
\par
Pros\par
\par
Autoencoders can handle high-dimensional data with ease. \par
Pertaining to its nonlinearity behavior, it can find complex patterns within high-dimensional datasets.\par
Cons\par
\par
Since it\rquote s a deep learning-based strategy, it will particularly struggle if the data is less.\par
Computation costs will skyrocket if the depth of the network increases and while dealing with big data.\par
So far we\rquote ve seen how to detect and identify anomalies. But the real question arises after finding them. Now what? What do we do about it?\par
\par
Let\rquote s discuss some of the pointers you could apply in your scenario.\par
\par
How to deal with the anomalies?\par
After detection, there comes a big question of what to do about the stuff we identified. There are numerous ways to deal with the newly found information. I\rquote ll list some of them based on my experience to give you a headway on how to approach this question.\par
\par
Understanding the business case\par
Anomalies almost always provide new information and perspective to your problems. Stock prices going up suddenly? There has to be a reason for this like we saw with Gamestop, a pandemic could be another. So, understanding the reasons behind the spike can help you solve the problem in an efficient manner.\par
\par
Understanding the business use case can also help you identify the problem better. For instance, you might be working on some sort of fraud detection which means your primary goal is indeed understanding the outliers in the data.\par
\par
If none of this is your concern, you can move to remove or smoothen out the outlier.\par
\par
Statistical methods to adjust outliers\par
Statistical methods let you adjust the value of your outlier to match the original distribution. Let\rquote s see one of the methods that use mean to smoothen out the anomalies.\par
\par
Using mean to smoothen out the outlier\par
The idea is to smoothen out the anomaly by using data from the previous DateTime. E.g., to even out a sudden usage of electricity due to an event that happened in your house, you could take an average of usages in the same month for previous years.\par
\par
Let\rquote s implement the same to get a clear picture. We\rquote ll employ the same catfish sales data we did earlier. We can adjust with the mean using the script below.\par
\par
adjusted_data = lim_catfish_sales.copy()\par
adjusted_data.loc[curr_anomaly] = december_data[(december_data.index != curr_anomaly) & (december_data.index < test_data.index[0])].mean()\par
Plotting the adjusted data and the old data will look something like this:\par
\par
plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))\par
plt.plot(lim_catfish_sales, color='firebrick', alpha=0.4)\par
plt.plot(adjusted_data)\par
plt.title('Catfish Sales in 1000s of Pounds', fontsize=20)\par
plt.ylabel('Sales', fontsize=16)\par
for year in range(start_date.year,end_date.year):\par
   plt.axvline(pd.to_datetime(str(year)+'-01-01'), color='k', linestyle='--', alpha=0.2)\par
plt.axvline(curr_anomaly, color='k', alpha=0.7)\par
